{"key":"post-14802366","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>14802366</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Also a lot of growers provide light to ALL stages of mycelium growth, colonizing jars, trays, monos, LC's, and even petri dishes. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I've recently concluded a series of tests with shiitake mycelium on petri dishes.&amp;nbsp; Mycelium in petri dishes grown in total darkness grew at less than half the speed of mycelium in dishes with normal ambient room light during the daylight hours.&amp;nbsp; Mycelium in petri dishes exposed to very bright light grew at about the same rate as those grown in total darkness.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Bottom line:&amp;nbsp; When colonizing, expose to ambient low-level lighting from day of inoculation.&amp;nbsp; When fruiting, expose to the brightest light possible without overheating the area.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>14802383</next>\n<prev>14802343</prev>\n<first>14802044</first>\n<last>14815182</last>\n<when>1311263290</when>\n<utime>07/21/11 06:48 PM</utime>\n</post>"}